1109779484###A bit more about proftpd and init scripts...###The stuff I posted the other day about writing an init script to start proftpd automagically worked great. Then I moved my Ultra down to my basement to make way for another development box with Linux as my 2nd desktop. Don't fret, this isn't my Linux fanfare, Solaris is still my fav, I'm just trying to broaden my horizons (that, and the fact I still for the life of me haven't figured out how to make the Ultra's Sound input work).&#13;<br>&#13;<br>Regardless, after it was moved it wouldn't start up anymore. Issuing a /etc/init.d/proftpd start errored out saying that it couldn't resolve the name of the computer. Basic Unix stuff here, if you don't use a DNS server, or I'd assume any other name server, you can add an entry to the /etc/hosts file for your computer. Fork is now using a static ip behind my firewall, so I added his name, and ip to the /etc/hosts file, and *poof* proftpd started using the normal command :)
1110754874###A Linux Tidbit...###OK so its not Solaris, but its *nix anyhoo...&#13;<br>&#13;<br>I ghosted my Laptop this weekend (Fedora Core 1 using the Sun Java Desktop system Gnome for those who wonder) and I used ghost 7.5...doh!&#13;<br>&#13;<br>It seems Ghost 8.0 and up support the GRUB boot loader and can restore it, otherwise, here's a tip on putting it back...&#13;<br>&#13;<br>http://service1.symantec.com/SUPPORT/ghost.nsf/docid/2000042113083825?Open&amp;src=csm&amp;docid=1999021909463125&amp;nsf=ghost.nsf&amp;view=docid/1999021909463125?open&amp;src=csm&amp;docid=2000033111503625&amp;nsf=ghost.nsf&amp;view=docid&amp;dtype=&amp;prod=norton%20ghost&amp;ver=&amp;osv=&amp;osv_lvl=&#13;<br>&#13;<br>You DID make the Rescue disk when it asked didn't you? If not, the CD1 of the install works just fine, just boot it up and when it asks type:&#13;<br>&#13;<br>linux rescue&#13;<br>&#13;<br>:)
1110947986###WiFi forwarding on my craptop...###http://yolinux.com/TUTORIALS/LinuxTutorialIptablesNetworkGateway.html&#13;<br>&#13;<br>Has a killer tutorial on setting up forwarding with Linux. I can attest that it works using my crappy lappy and an Orinoco Silver PCMCIA WiFi card to provide WiFi access to my new Viewsonic V37 PocketPC with an SDIO WiFi card from San Disk. It's being configured manually, I'm not using the DHCP server on Fedora yet.&#13;<br>&#13;<br>Now, none of this would really be needed if I had gotten that wireless router that I bought and paid for 3 weeks ago on ebay, though I haven't. I filed a PayPal claim, and the next day got tracking info stating that it had JUST been mailed out. Now it seems I don't really need it, bummer.&#13;<br>&#13;<br>Oh well, It'll probably go right back on the market if I decide its worth the time....LOL!
