1124736756###Remote XSession from Solaris to Linux###This is a cool thing. You can get a remote XSession including the CDE logon as a virtual terminal on a Linux box. Execute this from the Linux box:&#13;<br>&#13;<br>X (display #) -query (host of solaris box) &#13;<br>&#13;<br>ie: adam@wooble $&gt;X :2 -query fOrk&#13;<br>&#13;<br>This will put the Solaris XSession on to the 2nd virtual console. You can switch back and forth between the Linux PC and the Solaris console using CTRL+ALT+F# (use F5 for the Linux PC, if you use :1 Solaris will be on F6, if you use :2 Solaris will be on F7 and so on)
1128206369###2 New Packages!###Here's a couple new packages I've compiled. Lame 3.96.1 and Darkice 0.15.&#13;<br>&#13;<br>http://solaris.andarazoroflove.org/packages/darkice-0.15-sol11-sun4u-local.gz&#13;<br>&#13;<br>http://solaris.andarazoroflove.org/packages/lame-3.96.1-sol11-sun4u-local.gz&#13;<br>&#13;<br>Both were compiled on an Ultra 30, OpenSolaris 5.11 build 18. Compiled with GCC 3.4.2, installs in /usr/local.&#13;<br>&#13;<br>If anyone'd like my init script to launch shoutcast and darkice, leave a comment and I'll post it.
1128714251###Lame Compiling Error###Over the last week, I've re-built my SPARC computer from scratch with the latest (build 23) Solaris Express and the OpenSolaris BFU's. I ran in to some issues trying to compile Lame 3.9.6.1. I was getting an error like such:&#13;<br>&#13;<br>Error: Illegal operands: There are only 32 single precision f registers&#13;<br>&#13;<br>This was using the Solaris 10 Companion CD's version of GCC (3.4.2). So I tried installing the Blastwave GCC 3.4.4, again no such luck.&#13;<br>&#13;<br>After much Googling and trying different things, it seems that Sun's default ld (/usr/ccs/bin/ld) is not terribly compatible with GCC in its native format. I installed Blastwave's binutils (/opt/csw/bin) and linked them one by one in to (/usr/ccs/bin). YES I know I could have changed my pathing, but I didn't. All of the g utils are now in my /usr/ccs/bin and it compiled perfectly! &#13;<br>&#13;<br>Unorthodox to be sure, but I'm more concerned about it working...as for why it worked on my old install, the pathing WAS correct for use from /opt/csw/bin, and I have since changed it on the new install.
1130250956###CDE with VNC on Solaris###Someone asked me how to start CDE in a VNC session remotely. This isn't hard to do though I wondered why you'd want to. Basically CDE is fast. Even on old SPARC Hardware, CDE is responsive and easy to use. Plus I'm sure there are some diehard CDE fans out there still. (not that they wouldn't already know how to do this)&#13;<br>&#13;<br>Edit the file $HOME/.vnc/xstartup and it will look something like this:&#13;<br>&#13;<br>$defaultXStartup&#13;<br>= (&quot;#!/bin/sh\n\n&quot;.&#13;<br>&quot;[ -r \$HOME/.Xresources ] &amp;&amp; xrdb \$HOME/.Xresources\n&quot;.&#13;<br>&quot;xsetroot -solid grey\n&quot;.&#13;<br>&quot;xterm -geometry 80x24+10+10 -ls -title \&quot;\$VNCDESKTOP Desktop\&quot; &amp;\n&quot;.&#13;<br>twm &amp;&#13;<br>&#13;<br>As you can see, this sets up an xserver and starts twm as the window manager. To start CDE instead, simply replace the last line with:&#13;<br>&#13;<br>/usr/dt/bin/dtwm &amp;\n&#13;<br>&#13;<br>Consequently, you could also replace it with startgnome, gnome-session, or startkde. If you've installed XFCE, I believe the command is startxfce. This is certainly not a great tip, but useful none the less.
1130251368###Ultra 30 supports 15K RPM 36.4Gb Ultra320 SCSI###I'm posting this simply because I was not able to find any information about it while googling. The Sun Ultra 30 Service Manual (http://docs.sun.com/app/docs/doc/802-7719-12) does not give a whole lot of information on what type of drives the Ultra line supports. I'd suppose this is because Sun would prefer you purchase drives directly from them, but my Ultra is so far out of warranty, I'd rather eBay.&#13;<br>&#13;<br>Just as I was suprised to find that my old SPARCStation 20 would support 10K RPM 9.1Gb Seagate drives (whew they run HOT in that chassis though) I was just as suprised to find that my Ultra 30 easily supported a 15K RPM 36.4Gb Seagate SCSI SCA Ultra320 drive. I picked it up on eBay, surplus from an HP/Compaq server for $50.&#13;<br>&#13;<br>The Ultra 30 DOES support 15K RPM UltraSCSI drives. Plus it's tower design and 120mm fan in the front keeps them from overheating, but they do get warm to the touch. My Ultra lives in the basement where its always 60something and heat is not an issue...yet.
1130254863###QT Opensource Version Compiler Woes###So I'm trying to compile the QT Opensource version 4.0.1 and ran in to an odd error. I'd run the ./configure and get a message like:&#13;<br>&#13;<br>fOrk $&gt;./configure&#13;<br>&#13;<br>making qmake&#13;<br>gmake: CC: command not found&#13;<br>&#13;<br>Now I'm looking at that thinking CC? Did they mean cc? Of course. Doh! So I did this:&#13;<br>&#13;<br>root@fOrk #&gt;ln -s /opt/csw/gcc3/bin/gcc /usr/bin/CC&#13;<br>&#13;<br>QT will now compile. I guess I could have exported CC= in my path, but hey, why not make a symbolic link and never have to worry about it again?
1130255290###A BIG no-no for Solaris or is it?###One of the &quot;no-no&quot; things to do in Solaris is change the root user's shell. There are tons of discussions on why it is bad to do this and some on why it shouldn't matter. Here's a good FAQ about it:&#13;<br>&#13;<br>http://www.roble.com/docs/sol_root_shell.html&#13;<br>&#13;<br>Regardless, I did it. I changed root's shell to bash like so:&#13;<br>&#13;<br>fOrk $&gt;su - (this won't work if you are logged in as root)&#13;<br>Password: ********************* (yea my password is that long)&#13;<br>root@fOrk #&gt;usermod -s /bin/bash root&#13;<br>root@fOrk #&gt;exit&#13;<br>&#13;<br>That's it. I rebooted, crossing my fingers and poof my Ultra came right back up. Whew! If this was to break anything, I'd have simply &quot;boot cdrom -s&quot; from the Solaris install CDs and usermod'd it back to /bin/sh. Great tip, saved me from typing &quot;bash&quot; everytime after &quot;su&quot;.
1130383764###Solaris Audio Control###If you read this blog as infrequently as I post to it, you probably know that my Ultra is currently my shoutcast server. (mms://wooble.org:8080)The current set up is Shoutcast DNAS 1.95 SPARC, darkice .095, lame 3.97b, and an old Radio Shack PRO-110 100 channel scanner. &lt;/shamelessplug&gt;&#13;<br>&#13;<br>This is something that always perplexed me about Solaris, and I've finally figured it out, though its pretty trivial. The Solaris Audio Control tool is the program you need. Prior to discovering that (duh.) I was using kmix, which worked well but KDE is such a resource hog on 256mb of RAM. There is also another app available here: &#13;<br>&#13;<br>http://home.swipnet.se/~w-10694/utilities.html&#13;<br>&#13;<br>The command to run the Solaris Audio Control is:&#13;<br>&#13;<br>fOrk $&gt;/usr/dt/bin/stdaudiocontrol&#13;<br>&#13;<br>Wow. That's it. The command I never knew about because I don't use CDE enough and it's not on the menu in the Java Desktop System. (I think it should be, under Preferences) The Gnome audio tool that lives on the toolbar is only capable of mute, volume up, and volume down. If you double click it you are presented with 3 line levels which are locked in unison regardless. There is no choice for which input or output to use and the levels are named oddly. This command does exactly what the Gnome audio applet doesn't.
